<section xml:id="sec-percent-change" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
  <title>Percent Change</title>

  <introduction>
    <p>
        In <xref ref="sec-percent-change-prep"/>, we saw:
        <ul>
            <li>
                <p>
                    If Audryn left a $12.25 tip on a $68.00 bill, then she left an 18% tip. She paid $80.24 in totla, or 118% of the original bill.
                </p>
            </li>
        </ul>
        <ul>
            <li>
                <p>
                    If August bought a shirt that originally cost $25 but was 15% off, then he paid $21.25 for the shirt. The price he paid was 85% of the original price.
                </p>
            </li>
        </ul>
    </p>
    <p>
        We often describe increases and decreases in terms of percents.
        <ul>
            <li>
                <p>
                    The <term>initial value</term> is the original amount.
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <p>
                    The <term>percent change</term> or <term>relative change</term> is the percent increase or decrease from the initial value. The percent change is negative if it's a decrease.
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <p>
                    The <term>change factor</term> is the new value as a percent of the original value, divided by 100.
                </p>
            </li>
        </ul>
    </p>
  </introduction>
  <example>
    In the examples of Audryn and August, we have
    <table>
        <title>Examples of Percent Change Vocabulary</title>
        <tabular row-headers = "yes" halign="center" top="minor" bottom = "minor" right="minor" left="minor">
            <row header="yes">
                <cell></cell>
                <cell>Audryn</cell>
                <cell>August</cell>
            </row>
            <row>
                <cell>Initial Value</cell>
                <cell>68</cell>
                <cell>25</cell>
            </row>
            <row>
                <cell>Percent Change</cell>
                <cell>18%</cell>
                <cell>-15%</cell>
            </row>
            <row>
                <cell>Change Factor</cell>
                <cell>1.18</cell>
                <cell>0.85</cell>
            </row>
        </tabular>
    </table>
  </example>
  <p>
    The change factor is always
    <me>\frac{100 + \text{Percent Change}}{100}</me>.
  </p>

  <activity xml:id="a-find-change-factor">
    <task workspace="1in">
        <statement>
            <p>
                The city of Denver has a 9.15% sales tax. What is the change factor for the cost of items purchased in Denver?
            </p>
        </statement>
    </task>
    <task workspace="1in">
        <statement>
            <p>
                A store is having a sale and all of its items are 25% off. What is the change factor for the price of items in this store?
            </p>
        </statement>
    </task>
  </activity>

  <activity xml:id="a-notice-multiply-change-factor">
    <task workspace="1in">
        <statement>
            <p>
                Multiply <m>68 \times 1.18</m>. How does your answer compare to the total Audryn paid for her dinner?
            </p>
        </statement>
    </task>
    <task workspace="1in">
        <statement>
            <p>
                Multiply <m>25 \times 0.85</m>. How does your answer compare to what August paid for his shirt?
            </p>
        </statement>
    </task>
    <task>
        <introduction>
            <p>
                Mccoy bought a pair of earbuds in Denver for $79.99. 
            </p>
        </introduction>
        <task workspace="1in">
            <statement>
                <p>
                    Find the amount they paid after sales tax.
                </p>
            </statement>
        </task>
        <task workspace="1in">
            <statement>
                <p>
                    Multiply <m>79.99 \times \text{Change factor from }</m><xref ref="a-find-change-factor"/> part (a).
                </p>
            </statement>
        </task>
        <task workspace="1in">
            <statement>
                <p>
                    What do you notice about your answers?
                </p>
            </statement>
        </task>
    </task>
  </activity>

  <p>
    In <xref ref="a-notice-multiply-change-factor"/>, you should have noticed that
    <me>\text{New Value} = \text{Initial Value } \times \text{ Change Factor}</me>
  </p>

